Common.LongDescription.Common.Text:
The Starhill – the Home of the Tastemakers, is located in the heart of Bukit Bintang, Kuala Lumpur’s most famous shopping street and tourism belt. Offering experiential premium retail in a warm and sophisticated boutique retail environment, the revamped luxury mall due to re-open in 2021 will be replete with style and aesthetics of true tastemakers. Four floors of experiential retail space and three upper floors of JW Marriott Kuala Lumpur hotel rooms seamlessly integrate as one vertical seven-floor development – a first in Asia that truly breaks down the boundary between retail and hospitality. The Starhill will be connected to over 1,100 rooms of JW Marriott and The Ritz-Carlton, Kuala Lumpur. 

Highlights of the retail floors include luxury fashion, contemporary fashion, fine jewellery and timepieces, design galleries and lifestyle concepts complemented with cafes, lounges and restaurants including greenhouse-inspired culinary concepts in   conservatories. Truly the Home of the Tastemakers, a library concept will be the heart of the mall housing collections of books complemented with lifestyle products, F&B, services and event spaces.  The Starhill cements its place at the epicentre of Bukit Bintang, as the definitive lifestyle destination for discerning urbanites and travellers to enjoy best-of-class retail-hospitality experiences. The Starhill is a high-end retail asset owned by Starhill Global REIT listed in Singapore Exchange.

Common.LocationDescription.Common.Text: The F&B site is accessible via the Rail Corridor, which is about 200 m away from King Albert Park MRT Station and will welcome visitors into the community node.

Common.LongDescription.Common.Text:
The Conserved Railway Station Staff Quarters, which is designated for conservation under URA’s Draft Master Plan 2019, is a single-storey  house with a fair-faced brick facade.

The Rail Corridor was formerly a railway line that was used for commuting and transporting goods between Singapore and the rest of the Malay Peninsula at the beginning of the 20th Century. With the return of railway land to Singapore in 2011, the Rail Corridor will be developed into a continuous open space through the heart of Singapore where communities can forge new memories together.

The conserved Bukit Timah Railway Station is part of of Rail Corridor (Central), a signature 4km stretch between Hillview and the conserved Bukit Timah Railway Station.

Guided by the themes of Heritage and Culture, Biodiversity and Greenery, and Recreation, URA had started enhancement works along this stretch in 2019. Most of the works have since been completed, and Rail Corridor (Central) has reopened to the public as a more inclusive community space that brings nature, heritage and recreation closer to Singaporeans.

Common.LocationDescription.Common.Text:
Sembawang Park is a tranquil park away from the bustle of the city. With a beautiful beach side and a stunning view, it is a popular fishing ground and a great place for family and friends to get together.

Fitness enthusiasts can jog and swim while anglers cast their lines into the sea. Shelters and barbecue pits are located along the park and the beach, allowing families and friends to barbecue by the seaside. 

The park is also surrounded by other places of historical interest like the Admiralty House, Kampong Wak Hassan, Masjid Petempatan Melayu Sembawang, Sembawang memorial and the Sembawang Shipyard, which was a British Naval Base from 1938 to 1968.

Common.LongDescription.Common.Text:
Beaulieu House is located at the Northern seafront of Singapore in Sembawang Park. Set on a slope overlooking the jetty and waterfront of the Johor Straits, Beaulieu House has housed restaurants since 1981 and is a great spot for families and couples to relax and dine. 

Built sometime in the 1910s, Beaulieu House was owned by a Jewish family before it became the former lodgings of British naval officers. The single-storey bungalow's original neo-classical look and its Victorian cast iron work has remained intact. Beaulieu House received its conservation status in April 2005. 

To find out more, contact Adeline at 93636713.

Pasir Ris Park is a great place for families to have a fun day out. Aside from modern park activities such as pony rides, water sports and barbeque rental, it also features a carefully preserved six-hectare mangrove forest. The three-storey Bird Watching Tower located within the mangrove forest allows bird enthusiasts to observe birds in their natural surroundings. Families can also have hours of fun at the playground, one of the largest in Singapore.

Pasir Ris Park stretches from Pasir Ris Road to Jalan Loyang Besar and can be accessed through Elias Road and Pasir Ris Green.
